summary_points: 1. Cardinal Health Inc. issued $600,000,000 of 4.500% Notes due 2030 and $400,000,000 of 5.150% Notes due 2035 on August 13, 2025.
2.  The offering’s net proceeds to the issuer, after underwriting discounts but before estimated expenses, totaled $992,056,000.

3. The Underwriting Agreement contains extensive representations and warranties from Cardinal Health concerning the accuracy of its financial statements and compliance with various laws and regulations, including the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, the U.K. Bribery Act, and anti-money laundering laws, failure to comply with which could expose the company to significant financial and legal risks.
1. On August 14, 2025, Ball Corporation completed a $750 million public offering of 5.500% Senior Notes due 2033.
2. The Notes are senior unsecured obligations of Ball Corporation, guaranteed by substantially all its domestic subsidiaries.

3.  Ball Corporation may redeem the Notes at any time prior to June 15, 2033, at a price equal to 100% of the principal amount plus accrued interest, plus a "make-whole" premium; or on or after June 15, 2033 at 100% of the principal plus accrued interest.
1. Hubbell Inc. announced on August 12, 2025, a definitive agreement to acquire DMC Power, LLC for $825 million in cash, expected to close by the end of 2025.
2. DMC Power anticipates 2026 revenue of approximately $130 million and EBITDA of approximately $60 million.
3. Hubbell expects the acquisition of DMC Power to be accretive to adjusted EPS in 2026.
1. Dollar Tree, Inc. will discuss its second-quarter 2025 financial results during an earnings conference call on September 3, 2025.
2. The second quarter of 2025 ended on August 2, 2025.

1. Healthpeak OP, LLC, a subsidiary of Healthpeak Properties, Inc., completed a $500 million offering of 4.750% senior notes due 2033 on August 14, 2025, with estimated net proceeds of approximately $491.4 million.

2.  The net proceeds from the note offering are intended to repay borrowings under the commercial paper program and for general corporate purposes, including potential debt repayment, acquisitions, and capital expenditures.

3. The notes are guaranteed by Healthpeak Properties, Inc., and two of its subsidiaries, and are senior unsecured obligations, junior to existing and future secured indebtedness of Healthpeak OP, LLC and structurally subordinated to certain subsidiaries' liabilities.
1. Procter & Gamble Co's Chief Executive Officer – Beauty, Alexandra Keith, announced her retirement, effective February 20, 2026, after 36 years of service.
2.  Ms. Keith will not receive a cash severance payment upon retirement, but will retain a portion of her equity awards.
3. This 8-K filing, dated August 14, 2025, reports an event that occurred on August 12, 2025.

1. On August 14, 2025, Texas Pacific Land Corporation (TPL) announced a dual listing of its common stock on NYSE Texas, commencing trading on August 15, 2025, under the symbol "TPL," while maintaining its primary listing on the New York Stock Exchange.
2. TPL, headquartered in Texas, has been listed on the NYSE for over 130 years and is now a founding member of NYSE Texas.
3. The filing does not include any specific future impacts or risks associated with the dual listing.
1. Ulta Beauty, Inc. and Target Corporation mutually agreed to end their shop-in-shop partnership in August 2026.
2. The termination of the partnership is not anticipated to materially impact Ulta Beauty's fiscal 2025 financial results or previously stated long-term financial goals.
3. Ulta Beauty plans to launch Ulta Beauty Marketplace, a curated online platform aimed at attracting new brands and audiences, later in 2025.
1. On August 4, 2025, the company completed the sale of the Stuart Weitzman Business for $105.0 million.
2.  Total accrued liabilities were $736.9 million as of June 28, 2025, compared to $656.3 million on June 29, 2024.
3. The company expects to make a final payment of approximately $200 million during the first quarter of fiscal 2026 related to a stock repurchase program.
1. Tapestry, Inc. reported record fourth-quarter revenue of $1.7 billion (an 8% increase year-over-year) and record annual revenue of $7.0 billion (a 5% increase year-over-year) as of June 28, 2025.
2.  The Coach brand led revenue growth, with a 14% increase in the fourth quarter and a 10% increase for the full fiscal year 2025, while Kate Spade and Stuart Weitzman experienced declines.

3.  Tapestry projects low-single-digit revenue growth for fiscal year 2026 (approximately $7.2 billion), with a projected negative tariff and duty impact of approximately 230 basis points or $160 million; however,  they expect to offset this impact over time.
1. Deere & Company's Q3 2025 net income dropped 26% year-over-year to $1.289 billion, compared to $1.734 billion in Q3 2024.
2.  Full-year 2025 net income guidance was narrowed to $4.75 billion to $5.25 billion, due to customer caution and market uncertainty as of August 14, 2025.
3.  Worldwide net sales and revenues decreased 9% in Q3 2025 and 18% for the first nine months of 2025 compared to the same periods in 2024.
1.  No new information is provided in this section of the SEC filing that was not covered in the previous section.
1. On August 12, 2025, ONEOK, Inc. completed a public offering of $2.959 billion in notes, after deducting expenses, to repay existing debt and for general corporate purposes.
2.  The offering consisted of three tranches of notes: $750 million of 4.950% notes due 2032, $1.0 billion of 5.400% notes due 2035, and $1.25 billion of 6.250% notes due 2055.
3.  The notes are guaranteed by ONEOK Partners, L.P., ONEOK Partners Intermediate Limited Partnership, Magellan Midstream Partners, L.P., Elk Merger Sub II, L.L.C., and EnLink Midstream Partners, LP.
1. TransDigm Group Incorporated priced $5 billion in new debt on August 13, 2025, exceeding the initially announced $4 billion, to fund a special cash dividend of approximately $5 billion.
2.  The company expects to close $2.5 billion in new term loans by August 19, 2025,  as part of an amendment to its existing credit agreement.
3. The offering of the notes and credit agreement amendment are subject to customary closing conditions,  presenting a risk of these transactions not being completed as planned.
